`crates/ctx-cage/src/` is the sandboxing crate itself: it isolates an autonomous `claude` agent run's blast radius (filesystem, namespaces, network) while a separate host-side proxy is the only path bytes can leave through. Depending on this crate gets you a CLI (`ctx_cage`/`ctx_run` binaries) that resolves flags into a `Mode`/`Resolved`, hands that to `lifecycle::execute` for a guaranteed prepareâ†’runâ†’teardown cycle, and never lets a real API key or agent-cmd config reach the caged process directly.

The cross-cutting spine: `cli.rs` parses argv into a validated `Mode`, `lifecycle/` mints `Prep` and drives bwrap via `bwrap/`'s pure `build_bwrap_args`, `runtime.rs` resolves the host claude binary/credentials for billed launches, and `proxy.rs` + `proxy/head.rs` form the sole egress path, listening on a UNIX socket bind-mounted at `/run/ctx/api.sock`. Two invariants recur across every subsystem: (1) ADR-046 â€” `target_root` must be canonicalized and used as-is (no fixed alias), a rule shared by `bwrap/config.rs`, `lifecycle/env.rs`, and `runtime.rs`'s trust-map key; (2) the real API key/OAuth credential only ever reaches the proxy or runtime-synthesized config, never the cage's own environment â€” enforced independently by `lifecycle/env.rs`'s clearenv, `runtime.rs`'s narrow credential bind, and `proxy.rs`'s header injection.

`lib.rs` is the architecture doc plus two compiled-in assets (`CAGE_RULES_MD` agent doctrine, `CAGE_RESOLV_CONF` offline stub) that make misconfiguration a compile failure rather than a runtime one. `error.rs` supplies the crate-wide `CageError` (Io/Json/Protocol) that `runtime.rs`, `proxy.rs`, and `lifecycle/` all return into. `bin/` is the two CLI entry points sharing one sibling-binary resolution pattern; `bwrap/` is the sandbox-argv builder; `lifecycle/` is the phase orchestrator; `proxy/`+`proxy.rs` is the egress boundary; `runtime.rs` is host-claude/credential resolution.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory (or most of its subtree), so no divergence check is possible.